The Africa Centre for Disease Control (ACDC) has revealed that almost half of the persons who contacted the dreaded novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) in Africa’s COVID-19  have recovered from the disease. According to data published on the agency’s website out of the 433, 500 cases of the virus in Africa as of Friday, 3 June, 208, 400 of them have fully recovered and discharged. Prior to this report, there were fears that Africa will not be able to cope with the contagion which many felt will overwhelm the continent’s health systems. Since the first case of COVID-19 in the continent in February, southern Africa has the highest number of recoveries of 84, 697 out of 174, 327 infections Western Africa has 79,274 cases out of which 44,390 have recovered while eastern Africa takes the last position in recovery rates on the continent with 18, 351 case of infections. The agency further disclosed that there were 10,680 new COVID-19 recoveries in Africa on July 2, a majority of them with southern Africa countries leading 6,061 cases. On the flip side, however, 10, 658 persons have died from the disease with a greater number 4, 481 of them reported in northern Africa. Western Africa has 1,366 deaths from the virus, according to the latest data from the Africa CDC. Meanwhile, Nigeria, Africa’s most populous nation, on Thursday, crossed the 27,000 mark as the country reported 626 new COVID-19 infections. This is according to a tweet on the official handle of the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC)